{
  "id": "ch3",
  "course": "Katzung Pharmacology",
  "chapter": 3,
  "title": "Pharmacokinetics & Pharmacodynamics: Rational Dosing & Time Course of Drug Action",
  "subtitle": "High-Yield Summary",
  "sections": [
    {
      "id": "1-core-concept",
      "number": 1,
      "title": "Core Concept",
      "layout": "left",
      "reveal": "left",
      "blocks": [
        {
          "type": "text",
          "content": "Drug response depends on: **Dose → Concentration → Effect**"
        },
        {
          "type": "list",
          "items": [
            "**Pharmacokinetics (PK)** = what the body does to the drug:",
            "Absorption",
            "Distribution",
            "Metabolism",
            "Excretion"
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "list",
          "items": [
            "**Pharmacodynamics (PD)** = what the drug does to the body:",
            "Drug concentration–effect relationship"
          ]
        }
      ],
      "image": "data_3/01-fig-3-1.png",
      "imageCaption": "FIGURE 3-1 — Dose, concentration & effect (PK/PD)"
    },
    {
      "id": "2-volume-of-distribution",
      "number": 2,
      "title": "Volume of Distribution (Vd)",
      "layout": "right",
      "reveal": "right",
      "blocks": [
        {
          "type": "subheading",
          "content": "A. Volume of Distribution (Vd)"
        },
        {
          "type": "formula",
          "lhs": "Vd",
          "numerator": "Amount of drug in body",
          "denominator": "Plasma concentration"
        },
        {
          "type": "group",
          "label": "Meaning",
          "items": [
            "Apparent space containing the drug",
            "Large Vd → drug mainly in tissues",
            "Small Vd → drug remains mostly in plasma"
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "group",
          "label": "Examples",
          "items": [
            "**Digoxin** → very large Vd",
            "**Gentamicin** → low Vd; mainly extracellular fluid"
          ]
        }
      ],
      "image": "data_3/05-table-3-2.png",
      "imageCaption": "TABLE 3-2 — Body compartment volumes (L/kg)"
    },
    {
      "id": "3-clearance",
      "number": 3,
      "title": "Clearance (CL)",
      "layout": "right",
      "reveal": "right",
      "blocks": [
        {
          "type": "subheading",
          "content": "B. Clearance (CL)"
        },
        {
          "type": "formula",
          "lhs": "CL",
          "numerator": "Rate of elimination",
          "denominator": "Drug concentration"
        },
        {
          "type": "group",
          "label": "Meaning",
          "items": [
            "Efficiency of drug elimination"
          ],
          "note": "FIG 3-2 panels B & D show elimination (clearance); panels A & C show distribution (Vd) — see previous slide."
        },
        {
          "type": "group",
          "label": "Major elimination organs",
          "items": [
            "Kidney",
            "Liver"
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "text",
          "content": "Total clearance: ```text CLtotal = CLrenal + CLhepatic + CLother ```"
        }
      ],
      "image": "data_3/04-fig-3-2.png",
      "imageCaption": "FIGURE 3-2 — Elimination models (panels B & D)"
    },
    {
      "id": "4-half-life",
      "number": 4,
      "title": "Half-Life (t½)",
      "layout": "right",
      "reveal": "right",
      "blocks": [
        {
          "type": "subheading",
          "content": "C. Half-Life (t1/2)"
        },
        {
          "type": "formula",
          "expression": "t½ = 0.693 × Vd / CL"
        },
        {
          "type": "group",
          "label": "Meaning",
          "items": [
            "Time required for drug amount to decrease by 50%"
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "group",
          "label": "Rules",
          "items": [
            "1 half-life → 50% of the change is complete",
            "2 half-lives → 75% of the change is complete",
            "4–5 half-lives → about 94–97% of the way to steady state or elimination"
          ],
          "note": "t½ = 0.693 × Vd / CL — links Vd (slide 2), clearance (slide 3), and the elimination curves in FIG 3-2."
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "id": "3a-first-order-elimination",
      "number": 5,
      "title": "First-Order Elimination",
      "layout": "left",
      "reveal": "left",
      "blocks": [
        {
          "type": "list",
          "items": [
            "Most drugs follow first-order kinetics.",
            "A constant **fraction** of drug is removed per unit time.",
            "Rate of elimination is proportional to drug concentration.",
            "Results in a straight line on a log-concentration vs. time plot."
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "group",
          "label": "Examples",
          "items": [
            "Digoxin",
            "Theophylline",
            "Most antibiotics"
          ]
        }
      ],
      "image": "data_3/04-fig-3-2.png",
      "imageCaption": "FIGURE 3-2 — First-order elimination (panel B: exponential decay)"
    },
    {
      "id": "3b-capacity-limited-elimination",
      "number": 6,
      "title": "Capacity-Limited (Nonlinear) Elimination",
      "layout": "right",
      "reveal": "right",
      "blocks": [
        {
          "type": "list",
          "items": [
            "Elimination pathway becomes **saturated** at higher drug concentrations.",
            "Small dose increase → disproportionately large rise in plasma concentration.",
            "t½ is not constant — increases as dose increases."
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "formula",
          "lhs": "Rate",
          "numerator": "Vmax × C",
          "denominator": "Km + C"
        },
        {
          "type": "group",
          "label": "Examples",
          "items": [
            "**Phenytoin** — narrow therapeutic index; small dose change → large concentration change",
            "**Ethanol** — zero-order at typical drinking doses",
            "**Salicylates** at high/toxic concentrations"
          ]
        }
      ],
      "image": "data_3/04-fig-3-2.png",
      "imageCaption": "FIGURE 3-2 — Drug elimination models"
    },
    {
      "id": "3c-flow-dependent-elimination",
      "number": 7,
      "title": "Flow-Dependent Elimination",
      "layout": "left",
      "reveal": "left",
      "blocks": [
        {
          "type": "list",
          "items": [
            "Elimination rate depends primarily on organ **blood flow**, not enzyme capacity.",
            "Liver extracts nearly all drug on each pass — enzyme activity is not the bottleneck.",
            "Hepatic extraction ratio is high (>0.7)."
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "group",
          "label": "Clinical implication",
          "items": [
            "Reduced hepatic blood flow (e.g., heart failure, cirrhosis) → slower elimination → drug accumulation."
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "group",
          "label": "Examples",
          "items": [
            "Morphine",
            "Lidocaine",
            "Propranolol"
          ]
        }
      ],
      "image": "data_3/04-fig-3-2.png",
      "imageCaption": "FIGURE 3-2 — Drug distribution & elimination models"
    },
    {
      "id": "4-drug-accumulation",
      "number": 6,
      "title": "Drug Accumulation",
      "layout": "left",
      "reveal": "left",
      "blocks": [
        {
          "type": "text",
          "content": "Repeated dosing causes accumulation until steady state."
        },
        {
          "type": "group",
          "label": "Depends on",
          "items": [
            "Dosing interval",
            "Half-life"
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "group",
          "label": "Rule",
          "items": [
            "Short dosing interval relative to half-life → more accumulation"
          ]
        }
      ],
      "image": "data_3/06-fig-3-3.png",
      "imageCaption": "FIGURE 3-3 — Drug accumulation & elimination (half-lives)"
    },
    {
      "id": "5-bioavailability-f",
      "number": 7,
      "title": "Bioavailability (F)",
      "layout": "right",
      "reveal": "right",
      "blocks": [
        {
          "type": "group",
          "label": "Definition",
          "items": [
            "Fraction of unchanged drug reaching systemic circulation"
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "text",
          "content": "IV drugs: ```text F = 1 ```"
        },
        {
          "type": "text",
          "content": "Oral drugs often have: ```text F < 1 ```"
        },
        {
          "type": "text",
          "content": "1. Poor absorption"
        },
        {
          "type": "text",
          "content": "2. First-pass metabolism"
        },
        {
          "type": "group",
          "label": "Examples",
          "items": [
            "Morphine → extensive first-pass effect",
            "Propranolol → high first-pass metabolism"
          ]
        }
      ],
      "image": "data_3/08-fig-3-4.png",
      "imageCaption": "FIGURE 3-4 — Bioavailability: rate vs extent of absorption"
    },
    {
      "id": "6-first-pass-effect",
      "number": 8,
      "title": "First-Pass Effect",
      "layout": "center",
      "reveal": "up",
      "blocks": [
        {
          "type": "text",
          "content": "Drug absorbed from the GI tract enters portal circulation, then passes through the liver before reaching systemic circulation."
        },
        {
          "type": "group",
          "label": "Consequences",
          "items": [
            "Reduced bioavailability",
            "Increased metabolite formation"
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "group",
          "label": "Routes that avoid or reduce first-pass effect",
          "items": [
            "Sublingual",
            "Transdermal",
            "Partial rectal route"
          ]
        }
      ],
      "image": "data_3/08-fig-3-4.png",
      "imageCaption": "FIGURE 3-4 — First-pass effect lowers bioavailability"
    },
    {
      "id": "7-routes-of-administration",
      "number": 9,
      "title": "Routes of Administration",
      "layout": "left",
      "reveal": "left",
      "blocks": [
        {
          "type": "table",
          "header": [
            "Route",
            "Key Feature"
          ],
          "rows": [
            [
              "IV",
              "100% bioavailability"
            ],
            [
              "Oral",
              "Convenient, first-pass effect possible"
            ],
            [
              "IM / SC",
              "Good absorption"
            ],
            [
              "Inhalation",
              "Rapid onset"
            ],
            [
              "Transdermal",
              "Slow prolonged release"
            ]
          ]
        }
      ],
      "image": "data_3/07-table-3-3.png",
      "imageCaption": "TABLE 3-3 — Routes of administration & bioavailability"
    },
    {
      "id": "8-loading-dose",
      "number": 10,
      "title": "Loading Dose",
      "layout": "right",
      "reveal": "right",
      "blocks": [
        {
          "type": "text",
          "content": "Used to rapidly achieve target concentration."
        },
        {
          "type": "text",
          "content": "Formula: ```text Loading dose = (Vd × Target concentration) / F ```"
        },
        {
          "type": "group",
          "label": "Purpose",
          "items": [
            "Useful when the target concentration is needed quickly, especially for drugs with long half-life"
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "group",
          "label": "Examples",
          "items": [
            "Digoxin",
            "Phenytoin"
          ]
        }
      ],
      "image": "data_3/04-fig-3-2.png",
      "imageCaption": "FIGURE 3-2 — Volume of distribution & loading dose"
    },
    {
      "id": "9-maintenance-dose",
      "number": 11,
      "title": "Maintenance Dose",
      "layout": "center",
      "reveal": "up",
      "blocks": [
        {
          "type": "text",
          "content": "Used to maintain steady-state concentration."
        },
        {
          "type": "text",
          "content": "Formula: ```text Dosing rate = CL × Target concentration ```"
        },
        {
          "type": "text",
          "content": "Oral dosing: ```text Dose = (CL × Target concentration × Dosing interval) / F ```"
        },
        {
          "type": "group",
          "label": "Main determinant",
          "items": [
            "**Clearance**"
          ]
        }
      ],
      "image": "data_3/10-fig-3-6.png",
      "imageCaption": "FIGURE 3-6 — Dosing frequency vs plasma concentration"
    },
    {
      "id": "10-concentrationeffect-relationship",
      "number": 12,
      "title": "Concentration–Effect Relationship",
      "layout": "left",
      "reveal": "left",
      "blocks": [
        {
          "type": "text",
          "content": "Drug effect often follows the **Emax model**."
        },
        {
          "type": "text",
          "content": "Key terms:"
        },
        {
          "type": "table",
          "header": [
            "Term",
            "Meaning"
          ],
          "rows": [
            [
              "Emax",
              "Maximal effect"
            ],
            [
              "C50 / EC50",
              "Concentration producing 50% effect"
            ]
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "group",
          "label": "Important",
          "items": [
            "Concentration changes do not always produce proportional effect changes."
          ]
        }
      ],
      "image": "data_3/01-fig-3-1.png",
      "imageCaption": "FIGURE 3-1 — Concentration–effect relationship"
    },
    {
      "id": "11-delayed-drug-effects",
      "number": 13,
      "title": "Delayed Drug Effects",
      "layout": "right",
      "reveal": "right",
      "blocks": [
        {
          "type": "text",
          "content": "1. Distribution delay"
        },
        {
          "type": "text",
          "content": "2. Slow receptor dissociation"
        },
        {
          "type": "text",
          "content": "3. Slow physiologic turnover"
        },
        {
          "type": "group",
          "label": "Examples",
          "items": [
            "Digoxin",
            "Warfarin"
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "group",
          "label": "Warfarin",
          "items": [
            "Rapidly inhibits VKOR",
            "INR effect is delayed because clotting factors have long half-lives"
          ]
        }
      ],
      "image": "data_3/09-fig-3-5.png",
      "imageCaption": "FIGURE 3-5 — Delayed drug effect (ACE inhibitor example)"
    },
    {
      "id": "12-schedule-dependent-toxicity",
      "number": 14,
      "title": "Schedule-Dependent Toxicity",
      "layout": "center",
      "reveal": "up",
      "blocks": [
        {
          "type": "text",
          "content": "Toxicity may depend on dosing pattern."
        },
        {
          "type": "example",
          "content": "Example"
        },
        {
          "type": "list",
          "items": [
            "Aminoglycosides"
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "group",
          "label": "Continuous infusion",
          "items": [
            "More nephrotoxicity"
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "group",
          "label": "Intermittent dosing",
          "items": [
            "Less renal uptake"
          ]
        }
      ],
      "image": "data_3/10-fig-3-6.png",
      "imageCaption": "FIGURE 3-6 — Peak/trough fluctuations with dosing interval"
    },
    {
      "id": "13-cumulative-drug-effects",
      "number": 15,
      "title": "Cumulative Drug Effects",
      "layout": "left",
      "reveal": "left",
      "blocks": [
        {
          "type": "text",
          "content": "Effect depends on total exposure."
        },
        {
          "type": "text",
          "content": "Important measure: ```text AUC = Area under the concentration-time curve ```"
        },
        {
          "type": "group",
          "label": "Examples",
          "items": [
            "Many chemotherapy drugs"
          ]
        }
      ],
      "image": "data_3/06-fig-3-3.png",
      "imageCaption": "FIGURE 3-3 — Accumulation with repeated dosing"
    },
    {
      "id": "14-target-concentration-strategy",
      "number": 16,
      "title": "Target Concentration Strategy",
      "layout": "right",
      "reveal": "right",
      "blocks": [
        {
          "type": "group",
          "label": "Goal",
          "items": [
            "Achieve desired therapeutic concentration"
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "text",
          "content": "1. Choose target concentration"
        },
        {
          "type": "text",
          "content": "2. Estimate Vd and CL"
        },
        {
          "type": "text",
          "content": "3. Calculate dose"
        },
        {
          "type": "text",
          "content": "4. Measure response or concentration"
        },
        {
          "type": "text",
          "content": "5. Adjust regimen"
        }
      ],
      "image": "data_3/10-fig-3-6.png",
      "imageCaption": "FIGURE 3-6 — Target concentration strategy"
    },
    {
      "id": "15-factors-affecting-drug-levels",
      "number": 17,
      "title": "Factors Affecting Drug Levels",
      "layout": "center",
      "reveal": "up",
      "blocks": [
        {
          "type": "subheading",
          "content": "A. Renal Function"
        },
        {
          "type": "group",
          "label": "Reduced renal clearance affects drugs such as",
          "items": [
            "Digoxin",
            "Aminoglycosides",
            "Use creatinine clearance for dose adjustment."
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "subheading",
          "content": "B. Hepatic Disease"
        },
        {
          "type": "text",
          "content": "May reduce metabolism."
        },
        {
          "type": "group",
          "label": "Examples",
          "items": [
            "Diazepam",
            "Propranolol"
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "subheading",
          "content": "C. Obesity"
        },
        {
          "type": "group",
          "label": "Affects Vd differently",
          "items": [
            "Lipophilic drugs → larger Vd",
            "Hydrophilic drugs → minimal change"
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "subheading",
          "content": "D. Edema / Ascites"
        },
        {
          "type": "text",
          "content": "May increase Vd of hydrophilic drugs."
        },
        {
          "type": "example",
          "content": "Gentamicin"
        },
        {
          "type": "list",
          "items": [
            "Gentamicin"
          ]
        }
      ],
      "image": "data_3/02-table-3-1.png",
      "imageCaption": "TABLE 3-1 — PK/PD parameters (selected drugs)"
    },
    {
      "id": "16-plasma-protein-binding",
      "number": 18,
      "title": "Plasma Protein Binding",
      "layout": "left",
      "reveal": "left",
      "blocks": [
        {
          "type": "text",
          "content": "Important mainly for interpretation of total drug concentration."
        },
        {
          "type": "group",
          "label": "Key proteins",
          "items": [
            "Albumin",
            "Alpha-1 acid glycoprotein"
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "group",
          "label": "Important point",
          "items": [
            "Changes in protein binding usually affect total drug concentration more than free drug effect."
          ]
        }
      ],
      "image": "data_3/02-table-3-1.png",
      "imageCaption": "TABLE 3-1 — Protein binding & drug parameters"
    },
    {
      "id": "17-therapeutic-drug-monitoring-tdm",
      "number": 19,
      "title": "Therapeutic Drug Monitoring (TDM)",
      "layout": "right",
      "reveal": "right",
      "blocks": [
        {
          "type": "group",
          "label": "Useful for drugs with",
          "items": [
            "Narrow therapeutic index",
            "Variable pharmacokinetics"
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "group",
          "label": "Examples",
          "items": [
            "Digoxin",
            "Lithium",
            "Aminoglycosides",
            "Phenytoin"
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "table",
          "header": [
            "Drug",
            "Sampling Note"
          ],
          "rows": [
            [
              "Digoxin",
              "Measure after distribution, usually at least 6 h after dose"
            ],
            [
              "Lithium",
              "Trough level"
            ],
            [
              "Aminoglycosides",
              "Peak/trough monitoring"
            ]
          ]
        }
      ],
      "image": "data_3/03-table-3-1.png",
      "imageCaption": "TABLE 3-1 — PK/PD parameters (continued)"
    },
    {
      "id": "18-digoxin-case-summary",
      "number": 20,
      "title": "Digoxin Case Summary",
      "layout": "center",
      "reveal": "up",
      "blocks": [
        {
          "type": "group",
          "label": "Patient",
          "items": [
            "Elderly",
            "Reduced renal function"
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "group",
          "label": "Key principle",
          "items": [
            "Digoxin clearance is mainly renal."
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "text",
          "content": "1. Estimate creatinine clearance"
        },
        {
          "type": "text",
          "content": "2. Calculate total clearance"
        },
        {
          "type": "text",
          "content": "3. Calculate maintenance dose"
        },
        {
          "type": "text",
          "content": "Example practical dose if clinically appropriate: ```text 125 mcg/day = one 125 mcg tablet daily, or two 62.5 mcg tablets daily ```"
        }
      ],
      "image": "data_3/03-table-3-1.png",
      "imageCaption": "TABLE 3-1 — Digoxin & renal dosing parameters"
    },
    {
      "id": "19-must-know-exam-pearls",
      "number": 21,
      "title": "Must-Know Exam Pearls",
      "layout": "left",
      "reveal": "left",
      "blocks": [
        {
          "type": "list",
          "items": [
            "Clearance determines maintenance dose.",
            "Volume of distribution determines loading dose.",
            "Half-life depends on both Vd and CL.",
            "Steady state is reached after about 4–5 half-lives.",
            "First-pass metabolism lowers oral bioavailability.",
            "Nonlinear elimination: phenytoin, ethanol, salicylates at high/toxic concentrations.",
            "Digoxin dose must be reduced in renal failure.",
            "Aminoglycoside toxicity depends on dosing schedule.",
            "Protein binding changes usually alter total concentration more than free concentration."
          ]
        }
      ],
      "image": "data_3/02-table-3-1.png",
      "imageCaption": "TABLE 3-1 — High-yield PK/PD parameters"
    }
  ],
  "introImage": "data_3/01-fig-3-1.png",
  "introImageCaption": "FIGURE 3-1 — Pharmacokinetics & pharmacodynamics"
}
